<!-- ============================================================
     MODULE 1: WHAT YOUR SCORE MEANS
     ============================================================ -->
<div class="apn-c-section" id="apn-c-m1">
  <div class="apn-c-wrap">

    <span class="apn-c-label">Module 01: 2 min</span>
    <div class="apn-c-divider"></div>
    <h2 class="apn-c-h2">What Your Score Means.</h2>

    <p class="apn-c-body apn-c-body-lg">
      A score of 66 to 85 places you in the Competitor tier. This is not a participation bracket. This is a real level of performance that fewer than half of athletes who take this assessment reach. The foundation is genuinely in place: consistent training, adequate protein most days, sleep above 6 hours most nights, and some form of supplementation hierarchy.
    </p>

    <p class="apn-c-body">
      That foundation matters. And it creates a specific problem. When the basics are working, it becomes harder to identify what's actually limiting you. The gains slow down not because you're doing less, but because the primary bottleneck is now a single gap rather than a systemic one. At Competitor level, effort is not the variable. Gap identification is.
    </p>

    <div class="apn-c-data-callout">
      <div class="stat" id="apn-c-score-display">72</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Your Competitor Score: top half of all athletes assessed</div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="apn-c-h3" style="margin-top:40px;">What Defines the Competitor Tier</h3>
    <p class="apn-c-body">
      Competitor athletes train consistently but not always with structured periodization. Protein intake is present but often not distributed optimally across the day. Sleep is adequate on most nights but not tracked or protected with deliberate protocols. Supplementation is happening, but the stack has not been tiered by mechanism and priority.
    </p>
    <p class="apn-c-body">
      The result: effort is real, results are real, but the return on effort is lower than it should be. That gap between effort and output is where this MasterClass operates.
    </p>

    <div class="apn-c-warning">
      <span class="apn-c-warning-label">Gap to Next Tier</span>
      <p style="margin:0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.65;color:#78350F;">
        Elite tier begins at 86. The average Competitor-to-Elite jump requires closing one primary gap completely, not improving all gaps partially. Athletes who attempt to address all gaps simultaneously improve 15 to 20% in each area. Athletes who close one gap ruthlessly improve 60 to 80% in that area, and see downstream improvements in all others. The mechanism: primary gaps create cascading deficits across sleep quality, muscle protein synthesis, and cortisol management.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="apn-c-h3">Where Most Competitor Athletes Get Stuck</h3>
    <p class="apn-c-body">
      The most common Competitor plateau comes from balanced effort. They train hard three to five days a week. They take their protein. They sleep okay. And they try to improve everything at once. The result is slow, marginal progress across every pillar with no decisive breakthrough in any of them. The fix is not more effort. It's concentrated effort on the right target.
    </p>

    <div class="apn-c-pull-quote">
      <p>"One gap is costing you more than all the others combined. Your immediate job is to find it. Everything after that is execution."</p>
    </div>

    <h3 class="apn-c-h3">One Immediate Insight</h3>
    <p class="apn-c-body">
      At 66 to 85, the performance ceiling is not your training volume, your supplement spend, or your motivation. It is the primary gap identified in your assessment. Fix that gap. The rest of your system rises with it.
    </p>

  </div>
</div>


<!-- ============================================================
     MODULE 2: THE COMPETITOR PERFORMANCE PROFILE
     ============================================================ -->
<div class="apn-c-section-alt" id="apn-c-m2">
  <div class="apn-c-wrap">

    <span class="apn-c-label">Module 02: 5 min</span>
    <div class="apn-c-divider"></div>
    <h2 class="apn-c-h2">The Competitor Performance Profile.</h2>

    <p class="apn-c-body apn-c-body-lg">
      Every tier has a signature. Understanding the Competitor profile is not about labeling where you are. It's about seeing exactly what's working, what's limiting you, and what the behavioral difference is between here and Elite.
    </p>

    <!-- 3 defining behaviors -->
    <h3 class="apn-c-h3" style="margin-top:40px;">Three Defining Competitor Behaviors</h3>
    <ol class="apn-c-number-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Consistent effort without consistent structure.</strong> Competitor athletes train hard. The session count is real. But programming often lacks periodization. Training load doesn't follow a planned wave. Exercises rotate without a progression model. Hard work is present; intelligent structure is not fully locked in. The difference in output between hard effort and structured effort is approximately 20 to 35% in strength adaptation over a 12-week training cycle.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>One bottleneck dominating all results.</strong> In the 66 to 85 range, there is almost always a single primary gap that is suppressing results across all other pillars. Suboptimal sleep reduces muscle protein synthesis by 18 to 25%, increases cortisol output by 15 to 21%, and reduces next-day training output by 10 to 15%. Poor protein distribution limits MPS even when total daily intake is adequate. The bottleneck is measurable. It's not vague.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Ready to systematize.</strong> Competitor athletes have outgrown random fitness. They know something is off. They feel the gap between their effort and their results. This is the exact moment where a system replaces guesswork, and the compound effect of structured performance begins.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <!-- Separator from Elite -->
    <hr class="apn-c-hr">
    <h3 class="apn-c-h3">What Separates Competitor from Elite</h3>
    <p class="apn-c-body">
      Elite athletes (86 to 100) have locked all primary gaps. Their training follows a progressive overload model with planned deloads. Protein is distributed across four or more meals, each exceeding the leucine threshold for muscle protein synthesis (approximately 3g leucine per meal). Sleep is protected with a consistent protocol: fixed wake time, cool room, no caffeine after noon. Supplementation is tiered by priority with mechanism-specific timing.
    </p>
    <p class="apn-c-body">
